That pure hate &lt;rp&gt;<br>
-------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
<br>
Xosha sank into her hotel room alone again. She had been back in the swing of the adventuring life again for just about a month now. <br>
<br>
That life of constant fear and anger. That life of killing and blood. That life that so few decided to follow, and so few finally survived to reach a glorious status among her people.<br>
<br>
The more she was out in the field, the more she knew it was just the place for her. The blood flying violently from her advesaries' wounds into her face, couting the black ringmail of her armor. Watching them clutch feebly at thier wounds, blood running far too fast, she would look in thier eyes and see that light of life dimming. <br>
<br>
And in those final moments, oh how they hated her!<br>
<br>
The seething and absolute finality of the death she had so gleefully given stunned them and eventually in those final seconds, led them to utter anger and frsutration.<br>
<br>
That pure hate...<br>
<br>
The thought of it all started this tiny fire in Xosha. Just the thought of it. Then, seeing them fall to her, knowing that she was the very tool of Innoruuk's divine mandate, started much more than a tiny fire, every blessed kill was another coal, a coal that did not die or ebb. <br>
<br>
It had been a month, and Xosha felt hot to the touch.<br>
<br>
***<br>
<br>
A knock came to Xosha's hotel room door early the next morning. It was dark, the lights of the town torches having been extinguished some few hours ago. <br>
<br>
Here in the Foreign Quarter, the least reputable section of Neriak, and certainly the lowest in regards to rank and honor, they did not waste such things as fuel and tinder. It was commonly thought that the human scum that lived in these parts were not worthy of such niceities. Xosha had herself walked the torch duty when she served in the inner-guard, and more than once she had not only extinguished the torches, but threw them into the small pools of moisture on the floor to prevent lighting in the future. True, such activites were purely spiteful and immature, but that was the way of the guards, and to have stompped on thier tradition while she was a member would have meant death for sure.<br>
<br>
The knock was soft and quick, as if hidden or scared of awakening any but the occupants. Xosha rolled out of bed, dressed in only bedding clothes, and padded softly to the door.<br>
<br>
&quot;Aye?&quot; She asked softly.<br>
<br>
&quot;Here is your information madam, that'll be three platinum for the service.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Frexian, there was a time when you would have done such service for free...&quot; Xosha mentioned softly.<br>
<br>
&quot;True lady, but there was a time when the mere service of you was an honor, the up and coming apprentice of famed Morrigu, now you are nothing, a guard who left the guard.&quot;<br>
<br>
Normally such acusations would infurriate Xo, but the sharp honesty of it was too true to punish the teller.<br>
<br>
Xosha sighed, &quot;Pass it under the door please.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;As you wish.&quot;<br>
<br>
Xosha passed the platinum under the small crack beneath the door, and simultaneously an envolope skitted past her and into the middle of the room. Xo turned to it and smiled, no writing on the envolope. The true sign of the infilltrater.<br>
<br>
Xosha sat down on the cold stone floor, pulled tombcarver from the sheath in her boot (she had recently taken to using another dagger in battle) and opened the wax on the letter.<br>
<br>
Inside the letter told a step by step detail of the how to and where to find one Erudite Heretic named Maugarim.<br>
<br>
&quot;Ahhh... the Harvest, I do believe you have just hired the most effective assassin in Neriak.&quot; Xosha snapped her fingers for emphasis. <br>
<br>
&quot;I also think you're getting more than you bargained for.&quot; Xosha smiled again. Oh she had plans for the Harvest, they would fullfill her needs well.<br>
<br>
From beneath her tunic in a small inner pocket, Xosha pulled out a red ring, the only one like it, for there was only one person who needed it. Engraved on the inside were the words &quot;Feteric Teh Nalana&quot;....<br>
<br>
Sisters of Iosse... <br>
